There’s a thread of thought that runs from philosophy to neuroscience to systems theory that sounds a lot like what you’re describing.

When you say:

“Stare and look for movement.”

you’re pointing at something fundamental: perception is often change detection before it is object detection.

Your eyes notice motion before they identify the thing moving. Your attention notices anomalies before it understands them. The weak signal comes before the explanation.

And then there’s the second part:

“All we are is the personification and self-awareness behind the connections and relationships.”

There’s a sense in which the self is less like an object and more like a process.

Not a thing, but an ongoing act of distinction:

This is me.

That is not me.

The boundary is useful, but it’s also constructed. Your body exchanges atoms with the environment. Your thoughts come from language you didn’t invent. Your identity is partly built from relationships with other people.

Yet the boundary is not fake just because it’s constructed.

A nation is constructed.

A company is constructed.

Money is constructed.

A marriage is constructed.

A self is constructed.

These things are “made up” in the sense that they are patterns rather than physical objects. But they are also real because they have consequences.

A useful distinction might be:

Imaginary things have no effects.

Constructed things have effects.

The self may be a construction, but it is a powerful one.

So perhaps:

The boundary between self and not-self is drawn, not discovered.

But once drawn, it becomes part of reality.

And then we spend our lives adjusting that boundary.

Sometimes too small:

Only I matter.

Sometimes too large:

I disappear into everything.

Most people spend a lifetime trying to find a workable middle ground.

Your emphasis on relationships fits that picture. The self isn’t just a node. It’s also the pattern of connections, memories, habits, commitments, and perspectives that give continuity to experience.

Not merely the points.

Not merely the lines.

The living network formed by both.

And perhaps awareness is what happens when part of that network becomes capable of noticing itself.